(THE superstition upon which this tale is founded is very general in) Tj
T*
(the East. Among the Arabians it appears to be common: it did not,) Tj
T*
(however, extend itself to the Greeks until after the establishment of) Tj
T*
(Christianity; and it has only assumed its present form since the) Tj
T*
(division of the Latin and Greek churches; at which time, the idea) Tj
T*
(becoming prevalent, that a Latin body could not corrupt if buried in) Tj
T*
(their territory, it gradually increased, and formed the subject of) Tj
T*
(many wonderful stories, still extant, of the dead rising from their) Tj
T*
(graves, and feeding upon the blood of the young and beautiful. In the) Tj
T*
(West it spread, with some slight variation, all over Hungary, Poland,) Tj
T*
(Austria, and Lorraine, where the belief existed, that vampyres nightly) Tj
T*
(imbibed a certain portion of the blood of their victims, who became) Tj
T*
(emaciated, lost their strength, and speedily died of consumptions;) Tj
T*
(whilst these human blood-suckers fattened--and their veins became) Tj
T*
(distended to such a state of repletion, as to cause the blood to flow) Tj
T*
(from all the passages of their bodies, and even from the very pores of) Tj
T*
(their skins.) Tj
T*
(In the London Journal, of March, 1732, is a curious, and, of course,) Tj
T*
(credible account of a particular case of vampyrism, which is stated to) Tj
T*
(have occurred at Madreyga, in Hungary. It appears, that upon an) Tj
T*
(examination of the commander-in-chief and magistrates of the place,) Tj
T*
(they positively and unanimously affirmed, that, about five years) Tj
T*
(before, a certain Heyduke, named Arnold Paul, had been heard to say,) Tj
T*
(that, at Cassovia, on the frontiers of the Turkish Servia, he had been) Tj
T*
(tormented by a vampyre, but had found a way to rid himself of the) Tj
T*
(evil, by eating some of the earth out of the vampyre's grave, and) Tj
T*
(rubbing himself with his blood. This precaution, however, did not) Tj
T*
(prevent him from becoming a vampyre[2] himself; for, about twenty or) Tj
T*
(thirty days after his death and burial, many persons complained of) Tj
T*
(having been tormented by him, and a deposition was made, that four) Tj
T*
(persons had been deprived of life by his attacks. To prevent further) Tj
T*
(mischief, the inhabitants having consulted their Hadagni,[3] took up) Tj
T*
(the body, and found it \(as is supposed to be usual in cases of) Tj
T*
(vampyrism\) fresh, and entirely free from corruption, and emitting at) Tj
T*
(the mouth, nose, and ears, pure and florid blood. Proof having been) Tj
